title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson
postcontent: Now you can own a piece of history with a revolver from the Smith & Wesson Classics line. The Classics bring timeless and coveted models back in production. Each model, known for its legendary performance, has been enhanced with modern advantages. Smith & Wesson Classics embody the best of both worlds.This small revolver, designed primarily for plainclothesmen and off-duty police officers, made its public debut at The International Association of Chiefs of Police conference in 1950. At the conference, the Smith & Wesson sales force asked the police chiefs to vote on a name for the new revolver. The most commonly suggested name was .38 Chief’s Special®. Designed with the needs of law enforcement officials in mind, the Chief’s Special proved to be a popular revolver for personal protection due to its size and weight. When Smith & Wesson adopted model numbers in 1957, the Chiefs Special became the Model 36.Smith & Wesson J-Frame revolvers have had your back since 1950. These small revolvers were designed to fire full power rounds and are as simple and easy to use as they are reliable. Available in various calibers and with three diverse hammer designs, it is no surprise that the Smith & Wesson J-Frame has become the most popular, small-frame, defense revolver on the market.

title: For Sale:  Better than new XD-S 9
postcontent: I have had an XD double stack for almost a year and love the gun and it’s features such as fiber optic front sight and double safeties that automatically go away when you present the gun without having to find and flip levers. I wanted to add a single stack gun so the XD-S was a no brainer since it had all the same features. I bought a XD-S and out of the box the trigger felt a little gritty when dry firing. I ordered and installed the PRP spring upgrade kit and polished a lot of the internals while I had the gun apart. It now has a much smoother trigger with a nice crisp break. I also bought an additional new Springfield 9rd mag with sleave at a gun show ($45). I was all set and took the gun out to shoot it for the first time. title: For Sale:  Civil War Lorenz Rifle
postcontent: Austrian Lorenz 1854 Rifle Musket. Appears this one saw service in our Civil War, and is in good condition. Over 300,000 were acquired by the North and South, second in quantity only to the British Enfield. While many were issued in the original .54 caliber,this one was bored out to @ .58 Cal.  The wood is beechwood. The iron mounts are generally smooth. The bolster, rear of breech and forward part of the lock plate show typical evidence of firing with corrosion from the percussion caps. The date “860” is visible on the lock - the Austrians used only the last three digits of the year, indicating the gun was made in 1860. Front sight is in place as is the original ramrod.  Example of a typical Civil War infantry arm acquired for both Southern and Northern Units in lieu of Springfields and Enfields. Many were acquired early in the War for to arm infantry regiments being organized by the Northern states (my ancestor reportedly carried one in the 3rd Mass Infantry, 1862-63).  Southern use included the Army of Western Tennessee, VMI, et al.
